500|$|... {{proposed}} using multidimensional reversible cellular automata as an encryption system. In Kari's proposal, {{the cellular}} automaton rule {{would be the}} <b>encryption</b> <b>key.</b> Encryption would be performed by running the rule forward one step, and decryption would be performed by running it backward one step. Kari suggests that a system such as this {{may be used as}} a public-key cryptosystem. In principle, an attacker could not algorithmically determine the decryption key (the reverse rule) from a given <b>encryption</b> <b>key</b> (forward rule) because of the undecidability of testing reversibility, so the forward rule could be made public without compromising the security of the system. However, Kari did not specify which types of reversible cellular automaton should be used for such a system, or show how a cryptosystem using this approach would be able to generate encryption/decryption key pairs.|$|E
